Data explenation:

  • timestamp - date when the current record was created
  • company - the name of the company where the employee works
  • title - the name of the job position
  • totalyearlycompensation - the employee's annual compensation
  • location - the city where the employee works
  • yearsofexperience - the employee's total number of years in commercial business
  • yearsatcompany - the number of years the employee workes in this company
  • gender - employee's gender
  • Race - employee's race
  • Education - education level of employee (high school, bachelor etc.)
  • Masters_Degree/Bachelors_Degree/Doctorate_Degree/Highschool/Some_College - dummy variables which show all educational achievements of the employee
  • Race_Asian/White/Two_Or_More/Black/Hispanic - dummy variables which show the race to which the employee belongs

In this research we decided to work with only USA, becuase data contains a lot of "NA's" and it will significantly impact the results of the model, also situation with income massively depend on employee`s location (different country - different salaries, economy etc.)

def remove_outliers():
    q1 = df['totalyearlycompensation'].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = df['totalyearlycompensation'].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3-q1
    left_boundary = q1 - 1.5*iqr
    right_boundary = q3 + 1.5*iqr
    df_pre = df[(df['totalyearlycompensation'] > left_boundary)\
                    & (df['totalyearlycompensation'] < right_boundary)]

    q1 = df_pre['yearsofexperience'].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = df_pre['yearsofexperience'].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3-q1
    left_boundary = q1 - 1.5*iqr
    right_boundary = q3 + 1.5*iqr
    df_out = df_pre[(df_pre['yearsofexperience'] > left_boundary)\
                    & (df_pre['yearsofexperience'] < right_boundary)]
    
    return df_out

Kolmogorov-Smirnov test

  • The null hypothesis is that distributions are equal $F(X)=G(X)$
  • The two sided alternative is that $F(X)≠G(X)$
  • The one sided 'less' alternative is that $F(X)<G(X)$
  • The one sided 'greater' alternative is $F(X)>G(X)$

$F(x)$ represent the gender=Male group and the distribution $G(x)$ will represent the gender=Female group. If the two sided test finds a significant p value, a follow up one sided test will be performed to see which distribution has the greater area under the curve for a given salary x

In [ ]:
def run_ks_test(ser1, ser2):
    alternatives = ['F(x) != G(X)', 'F(x) < G(x)', 'F(x) > G(x)']
    p1 = ks_2samp(ser1, ser2).pvalue
    p2 = ks_2samp(ser1, ser2, alternative='less').pvalue
    p3 = ks_2samp(ser1, ser2, alternative='greater').pvalue
    tests = [round(p1, 5), round(p2, 5), round(p3,5)]
    
    output_df = pd.DataFrame({'Test': alternatives,
                  'P-value': tests})
    return output_df

run_ks_test(df[df['gender']=='Male'].totalyearlycompensation, df[df['gender']=='Female'].totalyearlycompensation)
Out[ ]:
Test P-value
0 F(x) != G(X) 0.00000
1 F(x) < G(x) 0.00000
2 F(x) > G(x) 0.99448

Consequently, we reject the null hypothesis that these distributions are equal. As a follow up test we check to see which side of the test is significant.

The significant p-value for the one sided 'less' alternative indicates that for overall total compensation of Male and Female, $F(x)<G(x)$

This means that for a given salary along the scale x , there is a higher probability to be under that salary for an Female employee than a white employee.

plt.show()










    
    

















    
    















    
    



































What we see is a gender gap for 0-5 years of experiense being almost equall for all education levels(with a little loss for women). For 6-12 years of experience, gender gap becomes more random(with high compensation for women with Phd and much lower for College) - but generally, men are still in win. For 13+ years of experience, statistics drops dramatically - women start to earn less.























Conclusion¶
After fixing the experience levels and observing the gender compensation difference for the particular levels of education, we are now able do state that women on average receive less due to the gender discrimination or some other unobserved factors(e.g. biological features, resistance to overloads or work experience)

def remove_outliers():
    q1 = df['totalyearlycompensation'].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = df['totalyearlycompensation'].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3-q1
    left_boundary = q1 - 1.5*iqr
    right_boundary = q3 + 1.5*iqr
    df_pre = df[(df['totalyearlycompensation'] > left_boundary)\
                    & (df['totalyearlycompensation'] < right_boundary)]

    q1 = df_pre['yearsofexperience'].quantile(0.25)
    q3 = df_pre['yearsofexperience'].quantile(0.75)
    iqr = q3-q1
    left_boundary = q1 - 1.5*iqr
    right_boundary = q3 + 1.5*iqr
    df_out = df_pre[(df_pre['yearsofexperience'] > left_boundary)\
                    & (df_pre['yearsofexperience'] < right_boundary)]
    
    return df_out

def run_ks_test(ser1, ser2):
    alternatives = ['F(x) != G(X)', 'F(x) < G(x)', 'F(x) > G(x)']
    p1 = ks_2samp(ser1, ser2).pvalue
    p2 = ks_2samp(ser1, ser2, alternative='less').pvalue
    p3 = ks_2samp(ser1, ser2, alternative='greater').pvalue
    tests = [round(p1, 5), round(p2, 5), round(p3,5)]
    
    output_df = pd.DataFrame({'Test': alternatives,
                  'P-value': tests})
    return output_df

Conclusion¶
After fixing the experience levels and observing the race compensation difference for the particular levels of education, you could observe that we are not able to draw any conclusions about race discrimination at some level of eexperience, company or job title. It's easy to see that Black and Hispanic people tend to vary in the size of compensation for different experience/education/title. The reason for that is not a discrimination - it's a sample size being not big enough to segment it that hard and to derrive accurate conclusions. We can easily see that for White people and Asians (taking almost 90% of a sample), for different distributions of experience, education and other relevant factors, both races possess not that random compensation values - disturbance of compensation does not change. Of course this is just one dataset with its own biases and disproportions among different groups.

Regression Discontinuity Design¶






















Here to show the impact of covid on the total yearly compensation, we used Regression Discontinuity Design. We implemented two models that are supposed to aproxiate the impact of covid on income of software ingeneers. First - build the regression model with dummie variable that incates weather observation is before or after covid, fit this regression, and than test its significance and observe its cooficient(the cooficient actually will be the inpact on the income if significant). See this method in the next section. The other model is more complex, for data before and after covid we construct the regression. And after that the gap between the two regressions at the point of beginig of covid will be the inpact of covid on income.



















In [ ]:



     


def rrd_average(cutoff_date, coulmn_name):
  avarege_by_month['covid'] = np.where(avarege_by_month.index >= cutoff_date, 1, 0)
  avarege_by_month['distance'] = (avarege_by_month.index - cutoff_date).days
  df_before_cutoff = avarege_by_month[avarege_by_month['covid'] == 0]
  df_after_cutoff = avarege_by_month[avarege_by_month['covid'] == 1]
  X_before = df_before_cutoff['distance']
  X_before = sm.add_constant(X_before)
  y_before = df_before_cutoff[coulmn_name]
  model_before = sm.OLS(y_before, X_before)
  results_before = model_before.fit()

  X_after = df_after_cutoff['distance']
  X_after = sm.add_constant(X_after)  
  y_after = df_after_cutoff[coulmn_name]
  model_after = sm.OLS(y_after, X_after)
  results_after = model_after.fit()

  plt.scatter(df_before_cutoff['distance'], df_before_cutoff[coulmn_name], color='blue', label='Before Covid')
  plt.plot(df_before_cutoff['distance'], results_before.predict(X_before), color='red', linewidth=2, label='Before Covid Regression Line')

  plt.scatter(df_after_cutoff['distance'], df_after_cutoff[coulmn_name], color='green', label='After Covid')
  plt.plot(df_after_cutoff['distance'], results_after.predict(X_after), color='purple', linewidth=2, label='After Covid Regression Line')

  plt.axvline(x=0, color='black', linestyle='--', label='Covid')
  plt.xlabel('Days to Covid')
  plt.ylabel('Total compensation')
  plt.title('RDD: Regression Discontinuity Design')
  plt.legend()
  plt.show()
cutoff_date = pd.to_datetime('2020-01-01')
rrd_average(cutoff_date, 'totalyearlycompensation')

def rrd(cutoff_date, coulmn_name):
  df['covid'] = np.where(df.index >= cutoff_date, 1, 0)
  df['distance'] = (df.index - cutoff_date).days
  df_before_cutoff = df[df['covid'] == 0]
  df_after_cutoff = df[df['covid'] == 1]
  X_before = df_before_cutoff['distance']
  X_before = sm.add_constant(X_before)
  y_before = df_before_cutoff[coulmn_name]
  model_before = sm.OLS(y_before, X_before)
  results_before = model_before.fit()

  X_after = df_after_cutoff['distance']
  X_after = sm.add_constant(X_after)  
  y_after = df_after_cutoff[coulmn_name]
  model_after = sm.OLS(y_after, X_after)
  results_after = model_after.fit()

  plt.scatter(df_before_cutoff['distance'], df_before_cutoff[coulmn_name], color='blue', label='Before Covid')
  plt.plot(df_before_cutoff['distance'], results_before.predict(X_before), color='red', linewidth=2, label='Before Covid Regression Line')

  plt.scatter(df_after_cutoff['distance'], df_after_cutoff[coulmn_name], color='green', label='After Covid')
  plt.plot(df_after_cutoff['distance'], results_after.predict(X_after), color='purple', linewidth=2, label='After Covid Regression Line')

  plt.axvline(x=0, color='black', linestyle='--', label='Covid')
  plt.xlabel('Days to Covid')
  plt.ylabel('Total compensation')
  plt.title('RDD: Regression Discontinuity Design')
  plt.legend()
  plt.show()
cutoff_date = pd.to_datetime('2020-01-01')
rrd(cutoff_date, 'totalyearlycompensation')

First model show that after covid income starts to decrease slower, but the natural suggestion that it could be because of the rapidly growing inflation after start of covid. Next model takes inflation to the considiration. Here two regresion lines are almost onle line. It means that covid did not infuence total yearly compenstation according to data in our dataset.

Here we tried 4 different regressions for predicting total yearly compensation:


    

  1. linear model that uses all independent variables 
    2. 

  2. linear model that uses only sinificant independent variables(Testnig significance using t-test, and than exluding the less significnt variables, continue to the point where all variables are significant)
    3. 

  3. Same as 2 but using log of years of experience 
    4. 

  4. Same as 2 but using log of years of experience and log of years at the company.
Accoring to most of the metrics(R2, Adjusted R2, Log likelyhood) the best model is 2 - linear model that uses significant variables.
    5. 



In 2nd model covid dummie is significant at the significance level of 95% but for instance for significance 95,5% its insignificant. 
In average for this model impact of covid on total income is -6436.9174 and std of 2592.927 dollars.


But note that averege income according to our dataset is decreasing even before covid. This means that recordings after covid that are obviously later in time have smaller total income. And covid variable could only be with negative cooef just because of that.
